article.description: Katie Smith scored 20 of her 22 points in the second half Friday night, leading the Minnesota Lynx past the Phoenix Mercury 75-51.
article.headline: Lynx get rare blowout win
article.linkText: Smith's 20 second-half points propel Lynx past Mercury
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Katie Smith scored 20 of her 22 points in the
second half Friday night, leading the Minnesota Lynx past the
Phoenix Mercury 75-51.

	   Tamika Williams added 12 for the Lynx (8-19), who won for just
the second time in the 13 games. The 24-point margin of victory
tied a team record.

	   Jennifer Gillom led the Mercury (9-18) with 12 points. Phoenix,
which led 29-27 at the half, has lost 19 games in a row on the
road.

	   "I felt it was one of our better halves but we didn't take the
opportunity presented to us,'' Mercury coach Linda Sharp said.

	   Smith, who sat out 13 minutes of the first half after picking up
three quick fouls, made nine of 10 from the field. The Lynx shot 54
percent (31-of-57), while the Mercury hit just 21-of-59 (36
percent) for the game.

	   "Katie was on fire in the second half,'' Lynx coach Heidi
VanDerveer said. "When you go nine-for-10 from the field, it can
be contagious. She got us going and everything fell into place.''

	   But Smith said she felt the key was that the team's defense
remained tight.

	   "We have had 10 point leads before and they have gotten away,''
she said.

	   Lynx center Michele Van Gorp hit a pair of baskets to put
Minnesota ahead for good with 18:13 left.

	   The victory was just the second for VanDerveer in eight games
since she took over the team on July 16.
